static char __pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_4CMR2___init__[] = "\n        Initializes a CMR2 object and prepares it to simulate the session defined\n        by pres_mat. [Modified by Beige]\n\n        :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the\n            simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a\n            dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n        :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be\n            presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number\n            of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to\n            range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity\n            matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to\n            zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.\n        :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n            words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n            match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n            row k-1 and column k-1.\n        :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n            should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n            matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n            position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n            features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n            kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param rec_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled\n            by the real subjects in a free recall phase on each trial. The rows are\n            corresponding to pres_mat. Used in simulating PEERS recogniti""on. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param ffr_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled\n            by the real subjects in a final free recall phase. Used in simulating\n            PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param cue_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are presented\n            to the model in recognition. Used in simulating recognition. (DEFAULT=None)\n        :param task: A string indicating the type of task to simulate. Set to 'FR' for free\n            recall or 'CR' for cued recall or 'Recog' for recognition. (DEFUALT='FR')\n        :param mode: A string indicating the type of task mode to simulate. For task = 'FR',\n            set to 'IFR' for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall; for task = 'CR',\n            set to 'Simultaneous' for simultaneous encoding or 'Sequential' for sequential encoding;\n            for task = 'Recog', set to 'Continuous' for continuous recognition or 'Final' for a\n            recognition in final stage. (DEFUALT='IFR')\n        ";

 0079:         """
 0080:         Initializes a CMR2 object and prepares it to simulate the session defined
 0081:         by pres_mat. [Modified by Beige]
 0082: 
 0083:         :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 0084:             simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a
 0085:             dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 0086:         :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be
 0087:             presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number
 0088:             of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to
 0089:             range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity
 0090:             matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to
 0091:             zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.
 0092:         :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 0093:             words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 0094:             match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 0095:             row k-1 and column k-1.
 0096:         :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 0097:             should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 0098:             matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 0099:             position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 0100:             features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 0101:             kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 0102:         :param rec_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled
 0103:             by the real subjects in a free recall phase on each trial. The rows are
 0104:             corresponding to pres_mat. Used in simulating PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)
 0105:         :param ffr_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are recalled
 0106:             by the real subjects in a final free recall phase. Used in simulating
 0107:             PEERS recognition. (DEFAULT=None)
 0108:         :param cue_mat: A 1D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that are presented
 0109:             to the model in recognition. Used in simulating recognition. (DEFAULT=None)
 0110:         :param task: A string indicating the type of task to simulate. Set to 'FR' for free
 0111:             recall or 'CR' for cued recall or 'Recog' for recognition. (DEFUALT='FR')
 0112:         :param mode: A string indicating the type of task mode to simulate. For task = 'FR',
 0113:             set to 'IFR' for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall; for task = 'CR',
 0114:             set to 'Simultaneous' for simultaneous encoding or 'Sequential' for sequential encoding;
 0115:             for task = 'Recog', set to 'Continuous' for continuous recognition or 'Final' for a
 0116:             recognition in final stage. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 0117:         """

Also provides options to update context and the model's\n        associative matrices after presentation. [Modified by Beige]\n\n        :param item_idx: The index of the cell within the feature vector that\n            should be activated by the presented item. If None, presents an\n            empty feature vector.\n        :param source: If None, no source features will be activated. If a 1D\n            array, the source features in the feature vector will be set to\n            match the numbers in the source array.\n        :param update_context: If True, the context vector will update after\n            the feature vector has been updated. If False, the feature vector\n            will update but the context vector will not change.\n        :param update_weights: If True, the model's weight matrices will update\n            to strengthen the association between the presented item and the\n            state of context at the time of presentation. If False, no learning\n            will occur after item presentation.\n        ";

(DEFAULT=60000)\n        :param max_recalls: The maximum number of retrievals (not overt recalls)\n            that the model is permitted to make. Use this setting to prevent the model\n            from eating up runtime if its parameter set causes it to make\n            hundreds of recalls per trial. (DEFAULT=np.inf)\n        ";

static char __pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_8run_cmr2_single_sess[] = "\n    Simulates a single session of free recall using the specified parameter set.\n    [Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n    :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the\n        simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be\n        presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number\n        of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to\n        range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity\n        matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to\n        zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'\n        for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')\n\n    :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model\n        recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each"" of\n        those items relative to the start of the recall period.\n    ";

 1259:     """
 1260:     Simulates a single session of free recall using the specified parameter set.
 1261:     [Unchanged from CMR2]
 1262: 
 1263:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1264:         simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a
 1265:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1266:     :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be
 1267:         presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number
 1268:         of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to
 1269:         range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity
 1270:         matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to
 1271:         zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.
 1272:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1273:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1274:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1275:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1276:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1277:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1278:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1279:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1280:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1281:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1282:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'
 1283:         for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 1284: 
 1285:     :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model
 1286:         recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each of
 1287:         those items relative to the start of the recall period.
 1288:     """

static char __pyx_doc_6CMR_IA_10run_cmr2_multi_sess[] = "\n    Simulates multiple sessions of free recall using a single set of parameters.\n    [Unchanged from CMR2]\n\n    :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the\n        simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be\n        presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number\n        of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to\n        range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity\n        matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to\n        zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.\n    :param identifiers: A 1D array of session numbers, subject IDs, or other values\n        indicating how the rows/trials in pres_mat and source_mat should be divided up\n        into sessions. For example, one could simulate two four-trial sessions by\n        setting identifiers to np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1]), specifying that the\n        latter four trials come from a different session than the first four trials.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the"" value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'\n        for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')\n\n    :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model\n        recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each of\n        those items relative to the start of the recall period.\n    ";

 1316:     """
 1317:     Simulates multiple sessions of free recall using a single set of parameters.
 1318:     [Unchanged from CMR2]
 1319: 
 1320:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1321:         simulation. Call the CMR2_pack_cyth.make_params() function to get a
 1322:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1323:     :param pres_mat: A 2D array specifying the ID numbers of the words that will be
 1324:         presented to the model on each trial. Row i, column j should hold the ID number
 1325:         of the jth word to be presented on the ith trial. ID numbers are assumed to
 1326:         range from 1 to N, where N is the number of words in the semantic similarity
 1327:         matrix (sem_mat). 0s are treated as padding and are ignored, allowing you to
 1328:         zero-pad pres_mat if you wish to simulate trials with varying list length.
 1329:     :param identifiers: A 1D array of session numbers, subject IDs, or other values
 1330:         indicating how the rows/trials in pres_mat and source_mat should be divided up
 1331:         into sessions. For example, one could simulate two four-trial sessions by
 1332:         setting identifiers to np.array([0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1]), specifying that the
 1333:         latter four trials come from a different session than the first four trials.
 1334:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1335:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1336:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1337:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1338:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1339:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1340:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1341:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1342:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1343:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1344:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of free recall to simulate. Set to 'IFR'
 1345:         for immediate free recall or 'DFR' for delayed recall. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 1346: 
 1347:     :returns: Two 2D arrays. The first contains the ID numbers of the items the model
 1348:         recalled on each trial. The second contains the response times of each of
 1349:         those items relative to the start of the recall period.
 1350:     """

Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a\n        dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.\n    :param data_dict: a dictionary contains pres_mat, rec_mat, ffr_mat, cue_mat.\n    :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all\n        words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must\n        match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along\n        row k-1 and column k-1.\n    :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat\n        should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The\n        matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial\n        position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source\n        features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the\n        kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)\n    :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')\n    :param mode: A string indicating the type of recognition to simulate. Set to 'Final'\n        for PEERS recognition. (DEFUALT='IFR')\n\n    :returns: Three dictionaries. The first contains the recognition response for each item.\n        The second contains the reaction time for each response. The third contains the\n        simulated context similarity for each item.\n    ";

 1382:     """
 1383:     Simulates multiple sessions of peers recognition using a single set of parameters.
 1384:     [Newly added by Beige]
 1385: 
 1386:     :param params: A dictionary of model parameters and settings to use for the
 1387:         simulation. Call the CMR_IA.make_params() function to get a
 1388:         dictionary template you can fill in with your desired values.
 1389:     :param data_dict: a dictionary contains pres_mat, rec_mat, ffr_mat, cue_mat.
 1390:     :param sem_mat: A 2D array containing the pairwise semantic similarities between all
 1391:         words in the word pool. The ordering of words in the similarity matrix must
 1392:         match the word ID numbers, such that the scores for word k must be located along
 1393:         row k-1 and column k-1.
 1394:     :param source_mat: If None, source coding will not be used. Otherwise, source_mat
 1395:         should be a 3D array containing source features for each presented word. The
 1396:         matrix should have one row for each trial and one column for each serial
 1397:         position, with the third dimension having length equal to the number of source
 1398:         features you wish to simulate. Cell (i, j, k) should contain the value of the
 1399:         kth source feature of the jth item presented on list i. (DEFAULT=None)
 1400:     :param task: Recognition. (DEFAULT='Recog')
 1401:     :param mode: A string indicating the type of recognition to simulate. Set to 'Final'
 1402:         for PEERS recognition. (DEFUALT='IFR')
 1403: 
 1404:     :returns: Three dictionaries. The first contains the recognition response for each item.
 1405:         The second contains the reaction time for each response. The third contains the
 1406:         simulated context similarity for each item.
 1407:     """
